While the conviction appeal was dismissed, the sentence appeal succeeded due to **unfairness**: the appellant’s predecessor (who initiated the policy) and two successors (who continued it) only faced disciplinary warnings, not criminal charges. The Court of Appeal ruled this disparity violated basic fairness, reducing the sentence to “time served” (4.5 months) to ensure the appellant was not penalized more harshly than colleagues involved in the same misconduct.  


